window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2025>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2025","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : PRINCIPLE OF MOMENTS","question":"You are provided with three sets of retort stands with clamps, two metre rules, a spiral spring, standard mass labelled m = 100\u2009g, and two pieces of thread with loops at both ends and a pointer.  Study the diagrams below.        Use the diagrams above as a guide to carry out the following instructions.    (i) With no load on the rule, attach the spring securely to it at T such that AT = 5\u2009cm.    (ii) Attach the loop of the thread securely to the rule at a point R such that RB = 5\u2009cm.    (iii) Ensure that the rule is horizontal as shown in Fig. 1(a).    (iv) Record the pointer position y1,\u200b on the vertical rule.    (v) Record the distance TR = L.    (vi) Suspend the mass, m = 100\u2009g at the point P on the horizontal rule such that PR = X = 20\u2009cm, as shown in Fig. 1(b).    (vii) Record the new pointer position y2\u200b.    (viii) Evaluate d = (y2 \u2212 y1).    (ix) Without changing the positions T and R, repeat the experiment for X = 25\u2009cm, 30\u2009cm, 35\u2009cm, and 40\u2009cm. For each case, record y2\u200b and evaluate d.    (x) Tabulate the results.    (xi) Plot a graph with d on the vertical axis and X on the horizontal axis, beginning each axis from the origin.    (xii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.    (xiii) Determine the value of K in the equation K = 100/s L \u200b.    (xiv) Use the graph to determine the pointer position y2\u200b when X = 32.5\u2009cm.    (xv) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"m = 100 g  y1 = 30.00 cm  TR = L = 90.00 cm    S/NAT(cm)RB(cm)X(cm)y2(cm)d = (y2 - y1)(cm)15.005.0020.0035.205.2025.005.0025.0035.605.6035.005.0030.0035.985.9845.005.0035.0036.406.4055.005.0040.0036.806.80      (xii) s=d2 - d1X2 - X1=6.48 - 5.4036.0 - 22.50=1.0813.5  \u2234 s = 0.08    (xiii) K=100sL=1000.08 \u00d7 90=1007.2=13.90    (xiv) Given that X = 32.50 cm. From the graph, d = 6.20 cm.    Since d = y2 - y1    y2 = d + y1 = 6.20 + 30 = 36.20    (xv) Precautions:    1. I ensured the metre rule was kept perfectly horizontal before taking any readings to avoid parallax and ensure accurate pointer displacement.    2. I avoided shaking or disturbing the setup while taking readings to prevent oscillations that could affect the accuracy of y\u2081 and y\u2082.    3. I ensured all clamps and threads were tightly secured to prevent any slipping or changes in the positions of T and R during the experiment.    4. I read all pointer positions at eye level to eliminate parallax error in the measurement of vertical displacement.    5. I allowed the spring to come to rest before taking y\u2082 readings to ensure the measured displacement is due to static extension only.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2025>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2025","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : PRINCIPLE OF MOMENTS","question":"State the principle of moment.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The principle of moments states that:    For a body in equilibrium, the sum of the clockwise moments about a point is equal to the sum of the anticlockwise moments about the same point.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2025>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2025","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"HOOKE\u2019S LAW, YOUNG\u2019S MODULES AND WORK DONE IN SPRINGS AND STRING :","question":"A block of mass 0.05\u2009kg is suspended on a vertical spring of force constant 5\u2009Nm\u22121. If the block extends 0.08\u2009m below the equilibrium position, calculate the magnitude of the net force on the block.  [g = 10\u2009ms\u22122]    (Please leave your answer with the unit e.g. 20 J)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"m = 0.05 kg, k = 5 Nm-1, x = 0.08 m, g = 10 ms-2    To find the net force on the block, we compare the weight of the block to the restoring force of the spring.    W = mg = 0.05 \u00d7 10 = 0.5 N    F = kx = 5 \u00d7 0.08 = 0.4 N    Fnet = W - F = 0.5 - 0.4    \u2234 Fnet = 0.1 N","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2025>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2025","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"You are provided with a drawing board, drawing paper, four optical pins, a rectangular glass prism, and other necessary materials.   Study the diagram below.        Use the diagram above as a guide to carry out the following instructions.    (i) Pin the drawing paper on the drawing board.    (ii) Trace the outline ABCD of the rectangular glass prism on the drawing paper provided.    (iii) Remove the prism. Select a point X on side AB such that it is one quarter of AB.    (iv) Draw the normal WXY, also draw a line RX, to make an angle \u0398 = 75&#176; with AB at X.    (v) Fix two pins at P1 and P2 on line RX. Replace the prism on its outline.    (vi) Fix two other pins at P3 and P4 such that they appear to be in a straight line with the images of the pins at P1 and P2 when viewed through the prism from side DC.    (vii) Remove the prism and the pins at P3 and P4. Draw a line to join P3 and P4.    (viii) Produce a line from P3 and P4 to meet the line DC at Z. Draw line XZ.    (ix) Measure and record the values of YZ and XZ.    (x) Evaluate \u03b1 =  YZ / XZ \u200b and Cos \u2061 \u0398.    (xi) Repeat the procedure for four other values of \u0398 = 65\u00b0, 55\u00b0, 45\u00b0, and 35\u00b0. For each case, evaluate \u03b1 and Cos \u2061\u0398.    (xii) Tabulate the results.    (xiii) Plot a graph of Cos \u0398 on the vertical axis and \u03b1 on the horizontal axis.    (xiv) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.    (xv) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate result.   (Attach your traces to this booklet.)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/N\u0398(\u00b0)YZ(cm)XZ(cm)\u03b1 = YZ/XZCos \u03981750.906.700.1340.2592651.806.800.2650.4233552.707.200.3750.5744453.307.400.4460.7075354.207.900.5320.819        (xiv) s=Cos \u03982 - Cos \u03981\u03b12 - \u03b11=0.700 - 0.2750.450 - 0.150=0.4250.300  \u2234 s = 1.417    (xv) Precautions:    1. I ensured all pins were fixed vertically to avoid parallax errors during alignment.    2. I viewed the pins with one eye closed and at eye level to correctly align the images during refraction.    3. I avoided parallax error when reading the protractor to measure angles accurately.    4. I maintained even spacing between the optical pins to enhance precision in alignment and tracing of the refracted ray.    5. I fixed the plain sheet of paper firmly on the drawing board to prevent it from shifting during tracing or pin insertion.    6. I avoided shaking or moving the setup while taking measurements to prevent distortion of the observed path.    7. I ensured the glass prism was placed exactly along the traced outline to maintain geometric accuracy.    8. I ensured adequate lighting so the pins and their images could be seen clearly through the prism.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2025>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2025","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"State the second law of refraction.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The second law of refraction, also known as Snell's Law, states that:    The ratio of the sine of the angle of incidence to the sine of the angle of refraction is constant for any two given media.    Mathematically:    sin isin r=n","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2025>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2025","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Light travels from air into glass of refractive index 1.5. If it is refracted at an angle 19.5\u00b0 to the normal, calculate the angle of incidence.    (Please leave your answer without the degree sign and to 1 d.p)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"n = 1.5, r = 19.5\u00b0, i = ?    n = sin isin r  1.5 = sin isin 19.5\u00b0  sin i = 1.5 \u00d7 sin 19.5    sin i = 1.5 \u00d7 0.3338    sin i = 0.5007    i = sin-1(0.5007)    \u2234 i = 30.0\u00b0","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2025>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2025","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"You are provided with a potentiometer, two cells, an ammeter, a voltmeter, a jockey J, a standard resistor and other necessary apparatus.  Study the circuit diagram below.        (i) Set up a circuit as shown in the diagram above.    (ii) Close the key, K.    (iii) Read and record the ammeter reading IO\u200b and the voltmeter reading VO\u200b when the jockey J, is not making any contact with the potentiometer wire OT.    (iv) Using the jockey, J make a contact with the potentiometer wire at a point S, such that OS = L = 10 cm.    (v) Read and record the ammeter reading I and the corresponding voltmeter reading, V.    (vi) Repeat the procedure for four other values of L = 20 cm, 30 cm, 40 cm and 50 cm.    (vii) For each case, read and record I and V.    (viii) Tabulate the results.    (ix) Plot a graph of V on the vertical axis and I on the horizontal axis starting both axes from the origin.    (x) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.    (xi) Determine the value of V when I = 0.    (xii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"IO = 0.49 A  VO = 2.51 V    S/NL(cm)I(A)V(V)110.00.542.46220.00.592.41330.00.662.34440.00.742.26550.00.852.15      (x) s=V2 - V1I2 - I1=2.0 - 2.51.0 - 0.50=-0.50.5  \u2234 s = -1.0    (xi) At I = 0, V = 3.0 volts    (xii) Precautions:    1. I ensured all connections were tight and clean to prevent energy loss or fluctuating readings.    2. I avoided pressing the jockey too hard on the wire to prevent damaging the wire or altering its resistance.    3. I ensured the key was opened when not taking readings to avoid unnecessary heating of the wire due to continuous current flow.    4. I checked that the voltmeter and ammeter were properly zeroed before starting the experiment.    5. I read both the ammeter and voltmeter at eye level to eliminate parallax error.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2025>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2025","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : PRODUCTION OF ELECTRIC CURRENT","question":"Explain how the local action defect in a simple cell can be corrected.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Local action in a simple cell is corrected by amalgamating the zinc electrode with mercury, which covers impurities and prevents the formation of small galvanic cells that cause unwanted corrosion.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2025>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2025","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"A potentiometer wire carrying a steady current is 100 cm long. When a standard cell of emf 1.5 V is connected, a balance length of 60 cm was obtained. If a cell of emf, E, gives a balance length of 80 cm, calculate E.    (Please leave your answer with the unit and to 1 d.p e.g 123.123 N)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Length of the potentiometer wire (L) =\u00a0100 cm    Emf of the standard cell (Estd\u200b) =\u00a01.5 V    Balance length for the standard cell (lstd) =\u00a060 cm    Balance length for the unknown cell (lunknown) =\u00a080 cm    Principle:    The potentiometer works on the principle that the\u00a0potential difference (V) across a uniform wire is directly proportional to the length (l) at which balance is achieved.    EunknownEstd=lunknownlstd  Eunknown1.5=8060  Eunknown=1.5\u00d78060=1.5\u00d743  \u2234 Eunknown = 2.0 V","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];